Spring Cloud is a rich ecosystem, so I'll walk you through it across multiple layers — 
      from the why to the how, with architecture diagrams and code examples at each level.

What is Spring Cloud and why does it exist?
  Before microservices, a typical Java app was a monolith: one WAR file, one database, one deployment unit. 
  As systems scaled, teams started splitting it into independent services. But that immediately introduced a new class of problems:
      How does Service A find Service B? (Service discovery)
      What if Service B is slow or down? (Resilience / circuit breaking)
      How do you manage 50 services' configs? (Centralized config)
      How do you trace a request across 10 hops? (Distributed tracing)
      How do you expose a single entry point? (API Gateway)

  Spring Cloud is the answer to all of these.
  It wraps proven patterns (from Netflix OSS, HashiCorp Consul, etc.) into Spring Boot autoconfiguration
  so you get production-grade distributed systems features with minimal boilerplate.

