Eureka — Service Discovery:
Why not hardcoded URLs?
Old pattern: http://order-service-host:8081/api/orders — hardcoded IP/hostname in configs.
             When services scale horizontally or move (Kubernetes, EC2), this breaks instantly.
Eureka: The Phone Book of Microservices
        Every service registers with Eureka at startup (heartbeat every 30s). 
        Any service wanting to call another asks Eureka: "Who's running order-service right now?"
<!-- Eureka Server -->
        <dependency>
          <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
          <artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-netflix-eureka-server</artifactId>
        </dependency>
        @SpringBootApplication
        @EnableEurekaServer
        public class EurekaServerApplication {
            public static void main(String[] args) {
                SpringApplication.run(EurekaServerApplication.class, args);
            }
        }
# Eureka Server: application.yml
      server:
        port: 8761
      eureka:
        client:
          register-with-eureka: false
          fetch-registry: false
        server:
          wait-time-in-ms-when-sync-empty: 0
<!-- Each microservice: Eureka Client -->
      <dependency>
        <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
        <artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-netflix-eureka-client</artifactId>
      </dependency>
# order-service: application.yml
    eureka:
      client:
        service-url:
          defaultZone: http://localhost:8761/eureka/
      instance:
        prefer-ip-address: true
// Calling another service by name, not IP
    @Service
    public class OrderService {
        // Spring Cloud LoadBalancer intercepts and resolves to a live instance
        @Autowired
        private RestTemplate restTemplate; // or WebClient
        public User getUser(Long userId) {
            return restTemplate.getForObject(
                "http://USER-SERVICE/api/users/" + userId,  // service name, not IP
                User.class
            );
        }
    }
@Configuration
public class RestTemplateConfig {
    @Bean
    @LoadBalanced  // ← enables service-name resolution via Eureka
    public RestTemplate restTemplate() {
        return new RestTemplate();
    }
}

Spring Cloud Gateway — API Gateway
Why not Zuul (the old way)?
    Zuul 1.x was blocking / Servlet-based. Spring Cloud Gateway is built on Project Reactor (non-blocking, reactive).
    It's the official modern replacement.
    Gateway is the single entry point — it handles routing, auth, rate limiting, request transformation, and CORS.
    <dependency>
      <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
      <artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-gateway</artifactId>
    </dependency>
    # Gateway: application.yml
    spring:
      cloud:
        gateway:
          routes:
            - id: order-service-route
              uri: lb://ORDER-SERVICE          # lb:// means load-balanced via Eureka
              predicates:
                - Path=/api/orders/**
              filters:
                - StripPrefix=1                # strips /api prefix before forwarding
                - name: RequestRateLimiter
                  args:
                    redis-rate-limiter.replenishRate: 10
                    redis-rate-limiter.burstCapacity: 20
            - id: user-service-route
              uri: lb://USER-SERVICE
              predicates:
                - Path=/api/users/**
                - Header=Authorization, Bearer.*   # only route if JWT present
              filters:
                - AddRequestHeader=X-Internal-Source, gateway
Custom global filter (e.g. JWT validation):
      @Component
      public class JwtAuthFilter implements GlobalFilter, Ordered {
          @Override
          public Mono<Void> filter(ServerWebExchange exchange, GatewayFilterChain chain) {
              String authHeader = exchange.getRequest()
                  .getHeaders()
                  .getFirst(HttpHeaders.AUTHORIZATION);
              if (authHeader == null || !authHeader.startsWith("Bearer ")) {
                  exchange.getResponse().setStatusCode(HttpStatus.UNAUTHORIZED);
                  return exchange.getResponse().setComplete();
              }
              // validate JWT, extract claims, pass through
              return chain.filter(exchange);
          }
          @Override
          public int getOrder() {
              return -1; // run before other filters
          }
      }

Resilience4j — Circuit Breaker, Retry, Rate Limiter:
Why not Hystrix?
Hystrix was Netflix's circuit breaker — it's now in maintenance mode. Resilience4j is its modern, lightweight, non-blocking replacement.
        failure rate             wait duration lapse
        > threashold
CLOSED------------------>OPEN<-------------------->HALF-OPEN
Calls pass through      Calls fail fast       Test limited calls

          probe fails → OPEN again
Half-Open----------------------->Closed
        probe calls succeed → back to CLOSED

<dependency>
  <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
  <artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-circuitbreaker-resilience4j</artifactId>
</dependency>

# application.yml — Resilience4j config
resilience4j:
  circuitbreaker:
    instances:
      userServiceCB:
        sliding-window-size: 10           # last 10 calls are evaluated
        failure-rate-threshold: 50        # >50% failures → OPEN
        wait-duration-in-open-state: 10s  # wait 10s before trying HALF-OPEN
        permitted-number-of-calls-in-half-open-state: 3

  retry:
    instances:
      userServiceRetry:
        max-attempts: 3
        wait-duration: 500ms
        retry-exceptions:
          - java.net.ConnectException
          - java.util.concurrent.TimeoutException

  ratelimiter:
    instances:
      apiRateLimiter:
        limit-for-period: 100            # max 100 calls per period
        limit-refresh-period: 1s
        timeout-duration: 0             # fail fast if limit hit

@Service
public class UserClient {
    private final RestTemplate restTemplate;
    private final CircuitBreakerFactory cbFactory;
    public UserClient(RestTemplate restTemplate, CircuitBreakerFactory cbFactory) {
        this.restTemplate = restTemplate;
        this.cbFactory = cbFactory;
    }
    public User getUser(Long id) {
        CircuitBreaker cb = cbFactory.create("userServiceCB");
        return cb.run(
            () -> restTemplate.getForObject("http://USER-SERVICE/users/" + id, User.class),
            throwable -> fallbackUser(id, throwable)   // fallback
        );
    }
    private User fallbackUser(Long id, Throwable t) {
        log.warn("Fallback triggered for user {} — {}", id, t.getMessage());
        return new User(id, "Unknown", "N/A");  // graceful degradation
    }
}
Annotation style (cleaner):
    @Service
    public class InventoryService {
        @CircuitBreaker(name = "inventoryCB", fallbackMethod = "fallbackStock")
        @Retry(name = "inventoryRetry")
        @RateLimiter(name = "apiRateLimiter")
        public StockInfo getStock(String productId) {
            return inventoryClient.getStock(productId);
        }
        public StockInfo fallbackStock(String productId, Exception e) {
            return StockInfo.unknown(productId);
        }
    }

5. OpenFeign — Declarative HTTP Client:
Why not RestTemplate / WebClient directly?
Writing restTemplate.getForObject("http://USER-SERVICE/users/{id}", User.class, id) is repetitive.
Feign lets you write an interface — Spring generates the HTTP client:
    <dependency>
      <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
      <artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-openfeign</artifactId>
    </dependency>
@SpringBootApplication
@EnableFeignClients
public class OrderServiceApplication { ... }
// Declare the client as an interface — no implementation needed
@FeignClient(
    name = "USER-SERVICE",               // matches Eureka registration name
    fallback = UserClientFallback.class  // Resilience4j integration
)
public interface UserClient {
    @GetMapping("/api/users/{id}")
    User getUserById(@PathVariable("id") Long id);
    @PostMapping("/api/users")
    User createUser(@RequestBody CreateUserRequest request);
    @GetMapping("/api/users")
    Page<User> getUsers(@RequestParam int page, @RequestParam int size);
}

// Fallback
@Component
public class UserClientFallback implements UserClient {
    @Override
    public User getUserById(Long id) {
        return User.empty(id);
    }
    // ...
}
// Using it — looks like a normal service call
@Service
public class OrderService {
    @Autowired
    private UserClient userClient; // Spring injects the generated HTTP client
    public OrderResponse placeOrder(OrderRequest req) {
        User user = userClient.getUserById(req.getUserId());
        // business logic
    }
}

Spring Cloud Bus — Event Propagation:
The problem it solves
When you update a config in Git and call /actuator/refresh on one instance, only that instance gets the new config. 
If you have 10 instances of order-service, you'd have to call all 10.
Spring Cloud Bus broadcasts a RefreshRemoteApplicationEvent over Kafka/RabbitMQ. All instances listen and refresh themselves.
  <dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-bus-kafka</artifactId>
  </dependency>
spring:
  cloud:
    bus:
      enabled: true
  kafka:
    bootstrap-servers: localhost:9092
Now a single POST /actuator/bus refresh on any instance refreshes all instances in the cluster.
You can also scope it: POST /actuator/busrefresh/order-service:** refreshes only order-service instances.

Distributed Tracing — Micrometer + Zipkin
Why you need it
In a monolith, one stack trace tells the full story.
In microservices, a single user request hops through Gateway → Order → User → Inventory. When something is slow, which service is the culprit?
Modern Spring Boot 3.x uses Micrometer Tracing (successor to Spring Cloud Sleuth), which adds a traceId and spanId to every request and propagates them via HTTP headers.
<dependency>
  <groupId>io.micrometer</groupId>
  <artifactId>micrometer-tracing-bridge-brave</artifactId>
</dependency>
<dependency>
  <groupId>io.zipkin.reporter2</groupId>
  <artifactId>zipkin-reporter-brave</artifactId>
</dependency>
management:
  tracing:
    sampling:
      probability: 1.0   # 100% in dev; use 0.1 in prod
  zipkin:
    tracing:
      endpoint: http://localhost:9411/api/v2/spans
Your logs will now automatically include:
INFO [order-service,4a6f2b1c3d8e9f0a,6c3d8e9f0a4b5c6d] Processing order 42
INFO [user-service,4a6f2b1c3d8e9f0a,7d4e9f0a5c6d7e8f]  Fetching user 7
Same traceId (4a6f2b1c...) across all services — search it in Zipkin and see the full request waterfall.

 Spring Cloud LoadBalancer
Replaces the old Netflix Ribbon (deprecated). Client-side load balancing — the service itself decides which instance to call.
@Configuration
public class LoadBalancerConfig {
    @Bean
    @LoadBalanced
    public WebClient.Builder webClientBuilder() {
        return WebClient.builder();
    }
}

@Service
public class OrderService {
    private final WebClient.Builder webClient;
    public Mono<User> getUser(Long id) {
        return webClient.build()
            .get()
            .uri("http://USER-SERVICE/api/users/" + id)  // service name resolved by LB
            .retrieve()
            .bodyToMono(User.class);
    }
}
Custom strategy:
// Round-robin is default. Switch to random:
@Bean
public ReactorLoadBalancer<ServiceInstance> randomLoadBalancer(
        Environment environment,
        LoadBalancerClientFactory factory) {
    String name = environment.getProperty(LoadBalancerClientFactory.PROPERTY_NAME);
    return new RandomLoadBalancer(factory.getLazyProvider(name, ServiceInstanceListSupplier.class), name);
}

