  ---------------------------------------------------
  @Service
  // No @RefreshScope here!
  public class PaymentService {
      @Value("${payment.api-key}")
      private String apiKey;  // NEVER refreshes -- captured at startup
  }
  CORRECT -- inject a @RefreshScope config bean:
  ----------------------------------------------
  @Service
  public class PaymentService {
      @Autowired
      private PaymentConfig paymentConfig;  // @RefreshScope bean, always fresh
      public void charge() {
          String key = paymentConfig.getApiKey();  // always reads current value
      }
  }
  WRONG -- @RefreshScope on @Configuration class:
  -----------------------------------------------
  @Configuration
  @RefreshScope   // DON'T do this -- @Bean methods won't refresh correctly
  public class DataSourceConfig {
      @Bean
      public DataSource dataSource() { ... }
  }
 
  CORRECT -- use @ConfigurationProperties instead:
  ------------------------------------------------
  @Component
  @ConfigurationProperties(prefix = "order")
  @RefreshScope
  public class OrderProperties {
      private int maxItems;
      private String paymentTimeout;
      // setters required for @ConfigurationProperties binding
  }
 
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 TRIGGERING REFRESH -- 3 WAYS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  1. Manual -- hit actuator on one pod:
     curl -X POST http://order-service:8081/actuator/refresh
  2. Spring Cloud Bus (Kafka) -- broadcasts to ALL instances:
     curl -X POST http://order-service:8081/actuator/busrefresh
  3. Spring Cloud Kubernetes Config Watcher -- AUTOMATIC:
     No curl needed -- watcher detects ConfigMap change
     and calls refresh on all pods automatically.
 
  application.yml -- enable the refresh endpoint:
  -----------------------------------------------
  management:
    endpoints:
      web:
        exposure:
          include: refresh, busrefresh, health, info
    endpoint:
      refresh:
        enabled: true
 
 ANSIBLE VAULT --> SPRING BOOT PROPERTIES (4 PATTERNS)
================================================================================
  OVERVIEW FLOW:
  --------------
  +------------------+
  |  Ansible Vault   |  (encrypted secrets store)
  +------------------+
         |
         +----------+----------+----------+
         |          |          |          |
         v          v          v          v
    [Pattern A] [Pattern B] [Pattern C] [Pattern D]
    Env Vars    app.yml     K8s Secret  HashiCorp
                Jinja2                  Vault
         |          |          |          |
         +----------+----------+----------+
                         |
                         v
              +--------------------+
              |  Spring Boot App   |
              | @Value/@ConfigProp |
              +--------------------+
  Priority (most secure to least):
  D (HashiCorp Vault) > C (K8s Secret) > B (Templated yml) > A (Env Vars)
 
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 PATTERN A -- Environment Variables (simplest)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  How it works:
  Ansible decrypts Vault secrets and sets them as env vars when starting
  the Spring Boot process. Spring Boot auto-maps env vars to properties
  using relaxed binding:
    SPRING_DATASOURCE_PASSWORD --> spring.datasource.password
  Ansible Playbook:
  -----------------
  - name: Deploy order-service
    hosts: app-servers
    vars_files:
      - vault/secrets.yml    # Ansible Vault encrypted file
    tasks:
      - name: Start Spring Boot service with secrets as env vars
        systemd:
          name: order-service
          state: restarted
        environment:
          SPRING_DATASOURCE_PASSWORD: "{{ db_password }}"
          PAYMENT_API_KEY: "{{ payment_api_key }}"
          SPRING_DATASOURCE_URL: "jdbc:postgresql://{{ db_host }}:5432/orders"
          SPRING_PROFILES_ACTIVE: "production"

  Spring Boot -- no special code needed:
  --------------------------------------
  @Value("${spring.datasource.password}")
  private String dbPassword;
  @Value("${payment.api.key}")
  private String apiKey;
  Drawback: secrets visible in 'ps aux' output -- low security.
 
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 PATTERN B -- Jinja2 Templated application.yml
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  How it works:
  Ansible templates the application.yml at deploy time, substituting
  Vault values before the app starts. File written to disk on the server.

  vault/secrets.yml (Ansible Vault encrypted):
  --------------------------------------------
  db_password: "prod_secret_xyz"
  api_key: "pk_live_abc123"
  redis_password: "redis_prod_pass"
  templates/application.yml.j2 (Jinja2 template):
  -------------------------------------------------
  spring:
    datasource:
      url: jdbc:postgresql://{{ db_host }}:5432/orders
      username: {{ db_user }}
      password: {{ db_password }}        # injected from Ansible Vault
    redis:
      password: {{ redis_password }}
 
  payment:
    api:
      key: {{ api_key }}
 
  order:
    max-items: {{ order_max_items | default(100) }}
 
  Ansible task:
  -------------
  - name: Template application.yml with vault secrets
    template:
      src: templates/application.yml.j2
      dest: /opt/order-service/config/application.yml
      owner: orderapp
      group: orderapp
      mode: '0600'                    # restrict read access
  - name: Restart service to pick up new config
    systemd:
      name: order-service
      state: restarted
 
  Spring Boot -- point to external config:
  ----------------------------------------
  spring:
    config:
      location: file:/opt/order-service/config/application.yml
  Drawback: secret written to disk, no dynamic refresh without restart.
 
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 PATTERN C -- Ansible Creates Kubernetes Secrets
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  How it works:
  Ansible decrypts Vault, creates K8s Secrets, Spring Boot reads them
  via Spring Cloud Kubernetes -- supports dynamic refresh.
  Ansible Playbook:
  -----------------
  - name: Create K8s secrets from Ansible Vault
    hosts: localhost
    vars_files:
      - vault/secrets.yml
    tasks:
      - name: Create K8s Secret for order-service
        kubernetes.core.k8s:
          state: present
          definition:
            apiVersion: v1
            kind: Secret
            metadata:
              name: order-service-secrets
              namespace: production
            type: Opaque
            stringData:
              spring.datasource.password: "{{ db_password }}"
              payment.api.key: "{{ api_key }}"
              spring.redis.password: "{{ redis_password }}"
 
      - name: Deploy order-service referencing the secret
        kubernetes.core.k8s:
          state: present
          definition:
            apiVersion: apps/v1
            kind: Deployment
            metadata:
              name: order-service
              namespace: production
            spec:
              template:
                spec:
                  containers:
                    - name: order-service
                      image: "yourregistry/order-service:{{ app_version }}"
                      envFrom:
                        - secretRef:
                            name: order-service-secrets  # inject all as env vars
 
  Spring Boot reads via @Value -- same as always:
  -----------------------------------------------
  @Value("${spring.datasource.password}")
  private String dbPassword;
  Advantage: K8s RBAC protects secrets, supports refresh via Config Watcher.
 
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 PATTERN D -- HashiCorp Vault + Spring Cloud Vault (most secure)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  How it works:
  Ansible provisions and unseals HashiCorp Vault with secrets.
  Spring Boot fetches secrets DIRECTLY from Vault at startup.
  Secrets NEVER touch disk or env vars.
  Dependency:
  -----------
  <dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-vault-config</artifactId>
  </dependency>
 
  bootstrap.yml (loaded before application.yml):
  -----------------------------------------------
  spring:
    application:
      name: order-service
    cloud:
      vault:
        host: vault.internal.company.com
        port: 8200
        scheme: https
        authentication: KUBERNETES         # pod uses K8s SA token to auth
        kubernetes:
          role: order-service              # Vault role mapped to this K8s SA
          kubernetes-path: kubernetes      # Vault auth mount path
        kv:
          enabled: true
          backend: secret                  # KV v2 mount
          default-context: order-service   # reads secret/order-service
          profiles:
            - production                   # also reads secret/order-svc/production
 
  Ansible writes secrets to HashiCorp Vault:
  ------------------------------------------
  - name: Write secrets to HashiCorp Vault
    hashivault_secret:
      url: "https://vault.internal.company.com"
      token: "{{ vault_root_token }}"      # from Ansible Vault
      secret: "order-service"
      mount_point: "secret"
      data:
        spring.datasource.password: "{{ db_password }}"
        payment.api.key: "{{ api_key }}"
 
  Spring Boot reads from Vault transparently:
  -------------------------------------------
  @Component
  @RefreshScope      // can re-fetch from Vault on refresh
  public class PaymentConfig {
      @Value("${payment.api.key}")           // comes from Vault at startup
      private String apiKey;
      @Value("${spring.datasource.password}")
      private String dbPassword;
  }
 
  Advantage: Full audit trail, secret rotation without restart,
             secrets never on disk, Vault leases auto-expire.
 
